This, after the motion of the vapours of which it consists has ceased, breaks up in a storm of rain, and, pressing by its weight on the underlying air and push- ing it out, causes the violent wind. But it is to be observed that although at some distance from the aforesaid mass of waters, boisterous winds blow and the sea is very rough, yet near the phenomenon all is calm, which l think may thus be explained. Since the: air is very dense at the outer edge of the vortex, as is seen in the figure, and is thrust out all round from the adrial vortex by the pressure of the superincumbent cloud, the winds carried towards the vortex are arrested and turned back by the air, which is very dense and also rushes in the opposite direction, so that their impulse cannot reach the vortex, yet meanwhile these winds driven backwards cause furious whirlwinds at some· distance from the said phenomenon.

It also makes for this, that the sea near the column of rising water is whirled round-a motion in water very much opposed to the propagation of waveS, which advance only in straight lines.
